X forwarding
============

xpra: rootless (ie la window s'affiche dans le wm hote)
x2go, nx (x2go est la version maintenue de freenx)
vnc, rdp (forwardent le desktop entier)
ssh -X

Rem: http://winswitch.org/ is a nice gui front end

Xephyr: version moderne de Xnest, supportant les extensions X modernes

Containers
==========

systemd-nspawn, libvirt-lxc, lxc

docker.io (wrapper autour des containers qui permet de faire des push/pull
et des trucs comme ça)
docker runs three ways:
  - as a daemon to manage LXC containers on your Linux host (sudo docker -d)
  - as a CLI which talks to the daemon’s REST API (docker run ...)
  - as a client of Repositories that let you share what you’ve built (docker pull, docker commit).

Non root containers
===================

mbox: http://pdos.csail.mit.edu/mbox/
Mbox is a lightweight sandboxing mechanism that any user can use without special privileges in commodity operating systems.

Integration continue
====================

travis (github), jenkins

Virtual box
===========

vagrant: wrapper
To achieve its magic, Vagrant stands on the shoulders of giants. Machines are provisioned on top of VirtualBox, VMware, AWS, or any other provider. Then, industry-standard provisioning tools such as shell scripts, Chef, or Puppet, can be used to automatically install and configure software on the machine.
packer: crée des images vagrant
https://github.com/elasticdog/packer-arch: un packer pour archlinux

openstack: le cloud open source

Configuration manager
=====================

chef, puppet, salt, ansible

